---
import ProjectDetail from '../../layouts/ProjectDetail.astro';
---

<ProjectDetail
  title="Recession Playlist"
  description="A work-in-progress study of whether aggregate music preferences correlate with economic conditions — do people reach for sadder, slower music when the economy turns dark?"
  tags={['Data Science', 'Spotify', 'FRED']}
  github="https://github.com/MariamKhubashvilii/music-economy"
  accent="pink"
  comingSoon={true}
>
  <section class="project-grid">
    <article class="project-card summary-card">
      <h2>Project summary</h2>
      <p>
        This research project investigates whether aggregate music preferences correlate with economic conditions. The core question: do people reach for sadder, slower, more introspective music when the economy turns dark? It merges Billboard chart history, Spotify audio features, and FRED economic indicators to find out.
      </p>
      <div class="summary-list">
        <div>
          <strong>Competing hypotheses</strong>
          <p>Tests mood reflection vs. mood regulation, and whether musical mood leads or lags the economy.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <strong>Status</strong>
          <p>Active work in progress — data integration and index construction are underway.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="project-card detail-card">
      <h2>What this project shows</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Merging Billboard, Spotify, and FRED data into one timeline.</li>
        <li>Monthly "mood indices" from chart and audio-feature data.</li>
        <li>Cross-correlation analysis at multiple lag periods.</li>
        <li>Regression and recession-vs-non-recession comparisons.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="project-section">
    <div class="section-content">
      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <p>
        The project tests four competing hypotheses about music and the economy, then works through four phases — from data integration to interpretation against existing academic literature.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">
        <div>
          <h3>Hypotheses</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>H1 — Mood reflection: valence declines in downturns</li>
            <li>H2 — Mood regulation: valence rises in downturns</li>
            <li>H3 — Leading indicator: mood shifts precede downturns</li>
            <li>H4 — Lagging indicator: mood shifts only after the data moves</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3>Method</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Integrate Billboard, Spotify, and FRED data</li>
            <li>Build monthly mood indices (optionally VADER lyrics)</li>
            <li>Cross-correlation and regression at multiple lags</li>
            <li>Interpret against the music-economy literature</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-section project-usage">
    <h2>Data &amp; caveats</h2>
    <p>
      Data comes from Billboard historical charts, Spotify audio-feature datasets, and the FRED API for economic indicators. The analysis is upfront about its limits — US-mainstream chart bias, audio features as imperfect proxies for emotion, correlation-vs-causation challenges, and blind spots for niche musical communities.
    </p>
    <div class="usage-card">
      <div>
        <strong>Data sources</strong>
        <p>Billboard charts, Spotify audio features, FRED economic indicators.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <strong>Best for</strong>
        <p>Anyone curious how cultural mood and macroeconomics might move together.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ProjectDetail>
